: The center of your Galton board is bin $helft.<br />To the left of bin $helft are $links marbles<br />To the right of bin $helft are $rechts marbles<br />The total amount of marbles left and right from bin $helft is $tot marbles.<br />We must calculate the probability: <b>P(X &le; $X | n=$tot , p = 1/2)</b>.<br />Using a scientific calculator (like Ti83) : <kbd>binomcdf($tot,1/2,$X)</kbd> &asymp; $kans &asymp; $rkans.<br />Because there is a double sided test [left/right]: H<sub>0</sub>:p=1/2 and H<sub>1</sub>:p &ne; 1/2<br />the p-value will be 2&times; $kans &asymp; $ans3  &asymp;$rans3<br />$ans3 $groter $[$perc/100] : $H0<br /><br />By the way, I&rsquo;ve re-adjusted the applet from P=1/2 to P=$chance .
: You&rsquo;ve dropped a total of $sum marbles...<br />In your Galton board with $bins bins, a marble will go $bins &minus; 1 = $[$bins -1] times to the left or right.<br /> In a perfect Galton board ( p = 1/2 ),  we would expect on average a marble to go $helft times to the right. <b>E</b>(X)=$[$bins-1] &times; 1/2 =$helft<br />&sigma;(X)=&radic;($[$bins-1] &times; 1/2 &times; 1/2) = $rsigma &asymp; $[round(1000*$sigma)/1000] <br />In your experiment the average is:<img src="$module_dir/gifs/barX.gif" alt="meanX"/> : $gemiddelde<br />P(X $groterP $gemiddelde | &mu; = $helft , &sigma; = $rsigma  / &radic;($sum))<br />Using the scientific calculator:<kbd><b>$normalcdf</b></kbd> &asymp; $roundkans &asymp; $rkans.<br />Because there is a two sided test  H<sub>0</sub>:&mu;=$helft and H<sub>1</sub>:&mu; &ne; $helft<br />the p-value is 2&times; $roundkans &asymp; $roundans3  &asymp;$rans3<br />$rans3 $groter $[$perc/100] : $H0<br />By the way, I&rsquo;ve re-adjusted the appletfrom P=1/2 to $chance .
